ce:section.ce:para:
Before applying the GQDs@PC@MIP nanoprobe to detect sulfadimethoxine in real samples, the removal of the template from the probe was evaluated. In the presence of sulfadimethoxine, the fluorescence emission of the hierarchical GQDs@PC@MIP nanoprobe was low (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). After the removal of sulfadimethoxine, fluorescence emission returned the same level as the hierarchical GQDs@PC@NIP nanoprobe. These results confirmed that the template was completely removed and the probe could be utilized to detect the target analyte in real samples.

The possible fluorescence quenching mechanism can be described by the Stern-Volmer equation [33]; F0/F = 1 + Ksv[CSulfadimethoxine], where F0 and F are the fluorescence emission intensity of the hierarchical composite GQDs@PC@MIP nanoprobe in the absence and presence of sulfadimethoxine, respectively, Ksv is the Stern-Volmer constant for sulfadimethoxine and [CSulfadimethoxine] is the quencher (sulfadimethoxine) concentration. A linear Stern-Volmer relationship was produced by the hierarchical composite GQDs@PC@MIP nanoprobe, which indicated a dynamic quenching process caused by electron transfer [15]. The electrons of GQDs were excited from ground state to excited state, without sulfadimethoxine around the GQDs@PC@MIP probe, the excited electron return to the valence band with producing fluorescence. Whereas, in the presence of sulfadimethoxine, the NH2 groups of the monomer can interact with sulfadimethoxine to form a Meisenheimer complex via hydrogen bonding. The interaction would lead to electron transfer from GQDs to sulfadimethoxine leading to fluorescence quenching. Furthermore, the UV absorption spectrum of sulfadimethoxine did not overlap with the emission spectrum of the GQDs@PC@MIP nanoprobe (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). Therefore, energy transfer was not a possible quenching mechanism [34].

The hierarchical composite GQDs@PC@MIP nanoprobe was utilized as an optosensor to detect sulfadimethoxine in milk (Table 1
                        ). The accuracy of the optosensor was evaluated by determining sulfadimethoxine in spiked milk samples at three different levels. Recoveries were between 86.8 and 98.9% with an RSD < 5%. The same concentrations of sulfadimethoxine in spiked milk samples were also determined by HPLC. The results obtained from the optosensor and HPLC method were in good agreement (Fig. 7
                        ). Chromatograms of milk samples spiked with different concentrations of sulfadimethoxine are shown in 
                           Fig. S4
                        . These results confirmed that the fabricated optosensor can be used as an accurate method for the detection of sulfadimethoxine in milk.
